A challenge for intro data viz

Point size, transparency, and faceting

11/17/2020

Im co-teaching an introductory coding class called R Data and Visualization (R-DAVIS) at UC Davis. This week, we worked on point size and transparency, and faceting ggplot() plots. In the interest of keeping things entertaining, I wanted to create a fun dataset that would allow students to practice plotting across groups in an interesting way. So, I decided to hide some fun data in a larger dataset that might be tricky to visualize. Below, you can find a guide on how I generated the data, and how the challenge was posed to students. A raw plot, even with faceting, will appear to be uninteresting:

However, if students adjust point size and transparency settings, they will find a hidden shape in each group!

The setup

This mini-project requires three libraries: raster::, RStoolbox:: and tidyverse::. raster:: lets us import the data, RStoolbox:: lets us convert imagery to a data.frame, and tidyverse:: does all the other heavy lifting. Lets load those. 

library(raster)
library(RStoolbox)
library(tidyverse)


Lets start with a few animal silhouettes. I got these from phylopic; all images hold no copyright.

First Ill import the images as raster datasets: 

#### Import data ----
dinoR = raster("data/dino_raw.jpg")
# http://phylopic.org/image/8b28eac0-15fc-4a3d-89c5-a6fcbd141a4a/
foxR = raster("data/fox_raw.jpg")
# http://phylopic.org/image/9c139682-7a9d-44e2-ae90-9be4624c2688/
fishR = raster("data/fish_raw.jpg")
# http://phylopic.org/image/6cf73e55-4e10-47ad-9b7e-33645536863f/
seahR = raster("data/seahorse_raw.jpg")

Next, for the data wrangling. Its a decent-sized chunk of code so its collapsed for visual purposes but you can open with the box.

Data wrangling

## Fortify
dinoF = fortify(dinoR)
foxF = fortify(foxR)
fishF = fortify(fishR)
seahF = fortify(seahR)

## Add group column
dinoF = dinoF %>%
  rename(Presence = dino_raw) %>%
  add_column(Group = "A")
foxF = foxF %>%
  rename(Presence = fox_raw) %>%
  add_column(Group = "B")
fishF = fishF %>%
  rename(Presence = fish_raw) %>%
  add_column(Group = "C")
seahF = seahF %>%
  rename(Presence = seahorse_raw) %>%
  add_column(Group = "D")

## Combine to single dataset
mydata = do.call("rbind",
                 list(dinoF,
                      foxF,
                      fishF,
                      seahF)) %>%
  filter(Presence != 255,
         Presence > 2)

## Generate several orders of random noise for masking data
mynoise = mydata %>%
  mutate(x2 = x + rnorm(nrow(mydata), 0, 10),
         y2 = y + rnorm(nrow(mydata), 0, 10),
         x3 = x + rnorm(nrow(mydata), 0, 50),
         y3 = y + rnorm(nrow(mydata), 0, 50),
         x4 = x + rnorm(nrow(mydata), 0, 100),
         y4 = y + rnorm(nrow(mydata), 0, 100)) %>%
  select(-x, -y) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(x2,x3,x4), 
               names_to = "axis1", values_to = "x") %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(y2,y3,y4), 
               names_to = "axis2", values_to = "y") %>%
  select(-axis1, -axis2, Presence)


## Combine noise and a strong signature of "true" data
fullData = rbind(mydata, mydata, mydata, mydata, mynoise)


Dont forget to save the data product! That data.frame(), after all, forms the core of the challenge for students. 

write.table(x = fullData,
            file = "data/mysteryData.csv",
            row.names = FALSE,
            col.names = TRUE,
            sep = ",")



The challenge


You are looking at a new dataset shared with you by a collaborator. You received the dataset shortly after the vernal equinox. Your collaborator didnt really give you any context on what the data represent, and you need to do some preliminary visualizations before you can really even formulate a question for them. Import the mystery dataset using: 

mystery <- read_csv("data/mysteryData.csv")
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   x = col_double(),
##   y = col_double(),
##   Presence = col_double(),
##   Group = col_character()
## )

Can you figure out what this dataset represents?
Hint Use your new knowledge of faceting to break up the data into groups, and consider changing the size and transparency of your geom_s to get a better look!

ANSWER

#### Visualize ----
myPlot = fullData %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  facet_wrap(~Group) +
  geom_point(size = 0.1,
             alpha = 0.01)
myPlot

ggsave("plots/clearPlot.jpg",
       myPlot,
       width = 5, height = 5,
       units = "in", dpi = 300)
